On January 24, 2023, about 1642 eastern standard time, a Piper PA-28-140 airplane, N7470R, 
 was substantially damaged when it was involved in an accident near Buford, Georgia. The 
 flight instructor and a student pilot were not injured. The airplane was operated as a Title 14 
 Code of Federal Regulations Part 91 instructional flight.
The flight instructor reported that she and the student pilot practiced several maneuvers in the 
 local area and were returning to their home airport. She asked the student to switch fuel tanks, 
 since it was time to do so. Shortly thereafter, the engine unexpectedly lost all power. She 
 confirmed that the throttle was full forward and the mixture was full rich. Unable to reach an 
 airport, the flight instructor performed a forced landing to a local interstate highway. During the 
 landing, the airplane’s nose landing gear collapsed and the right wing was damaged.
An inspector with the Federal Aviation Administration responded to the accident site and 
 examined the wreckage. He reported that the right wing was substantially damaged. 
The wreckage was retained for further examination.
